title: For Sale:  MINT WW2 GERMAN P38 PEBBLE-GRAIN HOLSTER WWII NAZI LATE WAR UNISSUED
postcontent: Original, unissued-condition WW2 German military holster for the P.38 service pistol. This example is MINT, clearly wartime manufacturer-stamped on rear " CXE " which was the wartime manufacture code for " cxe " ( for Britzer Eisenwerk Paul Szubinski, Britz Kreis Angermande), as well as P38.Interestingly, this example is marked " 4 ", likely intended for 45 date mark, but never stamped or obvious reasons, as the war came to an end.The leather on this holster is the desirable pebble-grain, just like ammo pouches and mapcases of early in the war. When holster manufacture switched to softshell from hardshell, nearly 95% of them were made of plain smooth leather to expedite manufacture and reduce cost. A very small number was made in pebble-grained leather.This holster is in excellent condition, with perfect white cotton-linen stitching throughout, no toe wear and no wear to the spare-magazine lower corners, and NO fraying, cracking or brittleness to the flap fold.A minty holster for the advanced collector. It will take ALL Walther, Mauser and SpreeWerke P.38s as well as the Postwar P.1s.$249 +  15 ship USPS Priority. I accept Paypal.

The rear sight is a combination sliding elevator/ladder sight. With the ladder folded down, the rear sight is a “U” notch on the top (rear) of the slider. The left side of the base is marked “1-5” for use with the slider as an elevator. When the ladder is raised, a small “U” notch on the top edge of the slider is used. The sides of the ladder are marked from “6-18” for use with the slider with the ladder raised. Stock Configuration & Condition: The stocks are three pieces, consisting of a buttstock, a nearly full length forend and a half-length handguard. The handguard is cut-out for the rear sight, which protrudes up through the handguard. There is a barrel band around the forend at the front of the handguard and another at the front of the forend. The forend has a nose cap which doubles as a bayonet mount and has a hole in its front face for storage of a cleaning rod. The belly of the buttstock is inlet for a sling swivel, but it is missing. There is a sling swivel at the bottom of the forward barrel band. The buttstock has a nearly flat military style steel butt plate with a tang at the top. There is light oil staining in the wrist and at the back of the forend and tiny spots of discoloration on the right side of the buttstock that could be water stains. There are a few dings and light bruises scattered over the stocks with two deeper dings on the right side of the forend, a small deep ding and a drag line in the handguard and a small deep ding in the underside front section of the forend. There is a small surface chip at the back edge of the lower tang and a small abraded spot just above the forend’s nose cap on the left side. The wood to metal fit is excellent and there are no cracks or chips showing. The LOP measures 13 1/8” from the front of the trigger to the back of the butt plate, which shows surface loss, light handling marks, a sharp ding on its right edge near the toe. The butt plate is in about Very Good condition. The stocks rate in about Fine condition. Type of Finish: The finish is blued with a case colored receiver and trigger guard. Finish Originality: There are no indications that the metal surfaces were ever refinished. Bore Condition: The bore is mostly bright, turning gray at the muzzle. The rifling shows very light wear and there is no erosion. Buyer will pay $25 for shipping
